fter dispossessing the country's propertied classes, Mao and the Communist Party took radical measures to eliminate class distinctions based on education, aggravating antagonisms between the new political and old cultural elites. Ultimately, however, Mao's attacks on both groups during the Cultural Revolution spurred inter-elite unity, paving the way-after his death-for the consolidation of a new class that combined their political and cultural resources. This story is told through a case study of Tsinghua University, which-as China's premier school of technology-was at the epicenter of these conflicts and became the party's preferred training ground for technocrats, including many of China's current leaders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aClasses socialesxHistoirex20e sièclexChine. 0aElite (Social sciences)xHistoryx20th centuryxChina. 0aEngineersxHistoryx20th centuryxChina. 0aIngénieursxHistoirex20e sièclexChine. 0aPouvoir (Sciences sociales)xHistoirex20e sièclexChine. 0aPower (Social sciences)xHistoryx20th centuryxChina. 0aSocial classesxHistoryx20th centuryxChina. 0aÉlite (Sciences sociales)xHistoirex20e sièclexChine. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477110840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804771108423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804771108.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles